# Read in data
total_data <- read.csv("Airline_customer_experience.csv", 
                       header = T, stringsAsFactors = T)

# Remove missing value & index column
total_data <- total_data[-which(is.na(total_data), arr.ind=TRUE), -1]

# Check if the data is imbalanced
total_obs <- dim(total_data)[1]
sum(total_data$Satisfaction == "dissatisfied") / total_obs
## [1] 0.4512358
# Create train & test data
set.seed(7)
train_data_indices <- sample(1:total_obs, 0.7*total_obs)
train_data <- total_data[train_data_indices, ]
test_data <- total_data[-train_data_indices, ]

Clustering

gower_dist <- daisy(total_data,
                    metric = "gower")
gower_mat <- as.matrix(gower_dist)

# Calculate silhouette width for many k using PAM
sil_width <- c(NA)
for(i in 2:10){
  pam_fit <- pam(gower_dist,
                 diss = TRUE,
                 k = i)
  sil_width[i] <- pam_fit$silinfo$avg.width
}

# Plot silhouette width
plot(1:10, sil_width,
     xlab = "Number of clusters",
     ylab = "Silhouette Width")
lines(1:10, sil_width)

total_data_s <- total_data
for(i in 1:ncol(total_data_s)){
  if(is.numeric(total_data_s[,i])){
    total_data_s[,i] <- scale(total_data_s[,i])
  }}

Even though the silhouette width is highest when the number of clusters is two, we should not use two as the clusters are too few to differentiate customers. As five clusters give a relatively high width and five is an appropriate number of clusters, we should group customers into 5 segments in this case.

pam_fit <- pam(total_data_s[,c(2:7)], k = 5)

centers <- pam_fit$medoids

# Scale back age and distance for observations
age_mean <- mean(total_data$Age)
age_sd <- sd(total_data$Age)
Flight.Distance_mean <- mean(total_data$Flight.Distance)
Flight.Distance_sd <- sd(total_data$Flight.Distance)

# Create a vector of cluster numbers
clusters <- c(1: 5)

# Extract centers
center_df <- data.frame(clusters, centers)
names(center_df)
## [1] "clusters"        "Gender"          "Customer.Type"   "Age"            
## [5] "Type.of.Travel"  "Class"           "Flight.Distance"
center_df$Age <- (center_df$Age * age_sd) + age_mean 
center_df$Flight.Distance <- (center_df$Flight.Distance * Flight.Distance_sd) + Flight.Distance_mean 

# print a table of features for each cluster
center_df

In order to maintain business success, companies should always examine the experience of high-value customers. For an airline, customers who bring the most value should be those who are loyal, fly long distance, and better in business class. Therefore, according to the values in Customer.Type, Class, and Flight.Distance shown above, the high-value customer segmentation should be cluster 3. Next, we will examine where the airline needs to make progress for cluster 3.

Examine Cluster 3 Customer Experience Issue

Based on the variable importance analysis at the end of this file, we know that cluster 3 customers care most about Inflight.entertainment, Ease.of.Online.Booking, and Seat.comfort.

# Check important variables for cluster 3
ie_3 <- mean(total_data$Inflight.entertainment[clusters == 3])
sc_3 <- mean(total_data$Seat.comfort[clusters == 3])

# Check non-important variables for cluster 4
eoob_3 <- mean(total_data$Ease.of.Online.booking[clusters == 3])

We can clearly see from the chart that the airline really need to improve their seats for high-value customers.

clusters <- pam_fit$clustering

plot(satisfaction_rate, type = "o")

From the graph above, cluster 2 is most dissatisfied with the airline experience. Therefore, currently the airline needs to focus on improving the experience of cluster 2 customers.

Dissatisfaction Reasons for Cluster 2

Based on variable important analysis, the most important variables for cluster 2 are Inflight.entertainment, Seat.comfort, and Ease.of.Online.booking. Therefore, we assume that the low satisfaction rate is mainly due to poor experience in these areas. Assumption tests are as follows.

Logistic Regression

lm_full <- glm(Satisfaction~., family = binomial, data = train_data)

Logistic Regression + Backward Selection

lm_bwd <- step(lm_full, direction = 'backward', k = log(nrow(train_data)), trace = T)

Parameter tuning

# Set possible values
mtry_vals <- c(2, 4, 5, 7, 9, 12, 15, 20, 22)
nodesize_vals <- c(1, 10, 15, 50, 100, 150, 200, 500, 1000)

params <- expand.grid(mtry_vals, nodesize_vals)
names(params) <- c("mtry", "nodesize")
acc_vec <- rep(NA, nrow(params))
spec_vec <- rep(NA, nrow(params))

# Loop through to find the best combination
for(i in 1:nrow(params)){
  rf_full <- randomForest(factor(Satisfaction) ~., # Set tree formula
                         data = train_data, # Set dataset
                         ntree = 200,
                         nodesize = params$nodesize[i],
                         mtry = params$mtry[i]) # Set number of trees to use
  rf_full_pred <-rf_full$predicted # Create predictions for bagging model

  t <- table(rf_full_pred, train_data$Satisfaction) # Create table
  c <- confusionMatrix(t, positive = "satisfied") # Produce confusion matrix
  
  acc_vec[i] <- c$overall[1]
  spec_vec[i] <- c$byClass[2]
}

res_db <- cbind.data.frame(params, acc_vec, spec_vec)
res_db$mtry <- as.factor(res_db$mtry) # Convert tree number to factor for plotting
res_db$nodesize <- as.factor(res_db$nodesize) # Convert node size to factor for plotting

# Plot the accuracy heatmap
g_2 <- ggplot(res_db, aes(y = mtry, x = nodesize, fill = acc_vec)) + # set aesthetics
  geom_tile() + # Use geom_tile for heatmap
  theme_bw() + # Set theme
  scale_fill_gradient2(low = "blue", # Choose low color
    mid = "white", # Choose mid color
    high = "red", # Choose high color
    midpoint =mean(res_db$acc_vec), # Choose mid point
    space = "Lab", 
    na.value ="grey", # Choose NA value
    guide = "colourbar", # Set color bar
    aesthetics = "fill") + # Select aesthetics to apply
